  "shortBio": "Gleamhares of Radiant Citadel, titled “Gleamcrest Keeper,” are mischievous radiant-touched Riftlings—four-footed and sure on uneven ground. In the wild they stay mischievous, four-footed and sure on uneven ground, and attentive to micro-changes in sunshaft and pale gold. Favorites include Radiant Lily. Their dawn joy talent shows first as caretaking, not combat.",
  "standardBio": "Gleamhare, titled among keepers as “Dawnshaft Companion,” carries hopeful duty in every movement. Native to Radiant Citadel, the species clarifies through sunshaft and pale gold, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a mischievous individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Radiant Lily eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Gleamhare silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their practical problem-solving intelligence makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Gleamhare's Sunshaft, reflects a life shaped by Radiant Citadel more than by arena ambition. Many assume Gleamhares are aggressive because of their radiant affinity; most are cautious first. Young Gleamhares practice Gleamhare's Sunshaft as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Gleamhares first condensed from residual prismdawn along the living edges of Radiant Citadel after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where sunshaft and pale gold gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Gleamhare returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Gleamhares as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Gleamhare into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Gleamhare care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Radiant Citadel still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Gleamhares often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is mischievous at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are four-footed and sure on uneven ground, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through glow-pulses along crest or plates. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as practical problem-solving intelligence. They sleep in warm stone hollows and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Gleamhares act as cleanup foragers within Radiant Citadel. Allies often include Celestora and Dawnkit; rivalries with Cinderquill and Emberfox are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. Travelers once claimed that following a wild Gleamhare through Radiant Citadel would lead them past a Rift storm unharmed. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Many assume Gleamhares are aggressive because of their radiant affinity; most are cautious first. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: When deeply bonded, a Gleamhare shares short dream-images of places it has never physically visited.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like frosted pearls veined with radiant light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor protective bursts, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Gleamhare is a living chapter of Radiant Citadel. Feed it Radiant Lily, respect its mischievous tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Gleamhare bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
